@RoyTellef,"Iran can legally, by international law, shut the entire Strait of Hormuz when e.g. attacked by the US!
Strait of Hormuz is 21 nautical miles wide, and the contiguous zone extends up to 24 nautical miles:
International Law:
The contiguous zone extends from 12 to 24 nmi, allowing limited, specialized jurisdiction for customs, fiscal, immigration, sanitary, and security laws. Territorial waters (or territorial sea) extend up to 12 nautical miles (nmi) from the baseline, providing full coastal state sovereignty. 

1. Territorial Sea (0–12 nmi): The coastal state exercises full sovereignty, including air space, water surface, seabed, and subsoil. Foreign ships enjoy ""innocent passage,"" but are subject to local laws.

2. Contiguous Zone (12–24 nmi): A ""buffer zone"" where the coastal state has limited control. It cannot exercise full sovereignty but can prevent/punish violations of its domestic laws (customs, immigration, INCLUDING WAR! etc.) that occurred within its territory.Key Differences: Sovereignty is total in the territorial sea, while only functional/limited in the contiguous zone.Relationship: The contiguous zone exists only in the space immediately beyond the territorial sea.

Btw;  there are no ceasefire, the US ended that the minute they blocked The Gulf of Oman, and when firing on an Iranian civil cargo ship (also an illegal act by international law). Actually; The entire Israeli/US war of aggression on Iran is illegal by international law! (look it up!)

